column9: So I'll start by saying I got this app to 1 - see which apps are using up the most battery, and 2 - to try and prolong my battery life. The app to me feels almost like some sort of Chinese scam app. A lot of stuff is in broken English and half the features don't really seem to do anything (such as optimizing your phone, it will always say there's issues even if you scanned 1 minute ago. Just as well I cannot see which apps are draining my battery, so the app is virtually useless. But I have yet to mention the worst feature yet, the ads. They are so intrusive, and I'm not talking about just when you have the app open, though there is plenty of that. Imagine you get off work, pull your phone out and unlock it, and you're greeted with ads that you have to close before you can actually use your phone. It's a really nice feature. I think I'll spend 3 dollars on the other battery app that doesn't make my phone feel like it's got a virus on it.

reviewTitle:
I'm not really sure if this app does what it says it does. I did not notice 
any appreciable difference. What I did notice is that the second I started 
this app more than 20 internet transactions occurred. And that happened 
before I was able to shut off its internet access. Now why would it want 
internet access but not list it in the permissions? I could understand a 
couple of Internet request to see if there's something new you need. But 
the amount of internet activity suggests something more along the lines of 
data mining. I can't prove that. I can only prove that it accesses the 
internet a lot. I have check the permissions access list located at the 
very bottom of the Google store app page. This app want so many permissions 
that it simply does not need. To me that suggests this app is doing some 
data mining. It may do what it says it does, but it also does a lot more 
you may not want.
